-- PRESS DIGEST- Financial Times - July 9
-- 
-- Tue Jul 08, 2014 07:17PM EDT
-- None



July 9 (Reuters) - The following are the top stories in the Financial Times. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

Headlines  Putin pauses for tactical rethink on Ukraine strategy (http://on.ft.com/1kBgmqF)  Short selling drops to lowest level since Lehman (http://on.ft.com/1znAJRZ)  Rajaratnam's brother acquitted by jury (http://on.ft.com/1oFiodu)  Maersk writes off $1.7 bln from Brazilian oilfields (http://on.ft.com/1stPNsu)  AbbVie lifts offer for Shire to 30 bln stg (http://on.ft.com/1k3hbIO)  Airbus staff quizzed in SFO probe into alleged Saudi corruption (http://on.ft.com/1jmRZlV)   Overview  After delivering a fierce speech to foreign diplomats in Moscow last week where he accused the United States of using cold war tactics, Russian President Vladimir Putin has gone oddly silent following the Ukrainian army's swift advance against pro-Russian separatists.  Hedge funds have taken the decision to reduce their bearish bets that the value of stocks is about to fall, with the share of stocks identified for short selling at its lowest level since before the financial crisis of 2007.  Rengan Rajaratnam, the younger brother of convicted Galleon Group founder Raj Rajaratnam, was on Tuesday cleared of a charge that he conspired to engage in insider trading while working at the $8 billion hedge fund.  Danish oil and shipping group AP Moeller-Maersk <MAERSKb.CO> revealed a $1.7 billion hit to its Brazilian oil assets, becoming the latest company to face issues trying to exploit the country's deepwater fields.  U.S. drugmaker AbbVie <ABBV.N> hiked its offer for Shire <SHP.L> to 30 billion pounds, even as it urged its shareholders to encourage the UK-listed drugmaker to partake in a friendly deal.